                        Berry
                    ) to the Secretary of
                            State</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1946v06</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d444</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">444</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1946-11-03T03:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1946-11-03T03:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-11-03T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-11-03T03:00:00-05:00" n="444" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d444">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">871.00/11–346: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Representative in Rumania</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Berry</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bucharest</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-11-03T10:00:00+02:00">November 3, 1946—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 4—4:18 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1027. Groza in expansive mood recently told of secret meeting with Tito.<note n="35" xml:id="d444fn35">Josip Broz-Tito, Yugoslav Prime Minister.</note>
                    Tito assured him as long as Moscow was satisfied with Rumanian Govt he had
                    nothing to ask from Rumania adding if there were Govt in Rumania with which
                    Moscow was not satisfied he would revise his attitude. Groza cited this
                    conversation as evidence that happy future of Rumania was closely tied to
                    continuation of his Govt. In same conversation he said his Govt planned to
                    strengthen the church in Rumania as it was weapon that would be used against the
                    imperialism of Vatican. In this connection he is drafting law arranging for
                    retirement of some independent-thinking bishops in Transylvania and replacement
                    by men more in sympathy with new DPM order.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Berry</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
